					<head>Esther scroll</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79053644" rend="visible">
						<summary>The Book of Esther. </summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="1r" to="1r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Megilat Ester </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מגלת אסתר</title>
							<note>
								<p>The quasi-heraldic device at the beginning of the scroll is signed: &quot;Salom. Italia sculpsit.&quot; The name of the original owner, which had been written on a blank space within the same design, has been erased, and a note of a later owner has been written down istead.  </p>
								<p>Below the design there is a date (in a recent hand), [5]629 (<date calendar="Gregorian">1869</date>).  </p>
							</note>
							<decoNote type="illustration">Copper-plate illustrations by <name type="person" role="artist">Solomon Italia</name>, inhabited, with architectural and floral designs.<locus from="1r" to="1v"/>
							</decoNote>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment scroll of the 17th century. </p>
						<objectDesc form="scroll ">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment. </support>
								<extent>5 membranes, 31 columns. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
										<height>130/155</height>
										<width>2690</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<collation>
									<p>5 membranes, with wooden roller. </p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Parchment slightly inflexible, with creases. </p>
									<p>Uneven trimming at lower edge and, in part, losses of printing at head.  </p>
									<p>Dark at edges and outer end (dirt and slight damp mottling).</p>
									<p>Usage and rust stains, a smear of green pigment on verso. </p>
									<p>One small loss to rodent at outer end. </p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="31" ruledLines="18" writtenLines="18">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Ruling by hard point,
membrane by membrane.</p>
									<p>Visible stiching of membranes. </p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side of membranes distinguishable. </p>
									<p>Three tagin on שעטנזגץ and one on בדהחיפף. </p>
									<p>A few majuscular or minuscular letters, ח being also arched. </p>
									<p>The names of the sons of Haman arranged in 11 lines, in accordance with the rule. </p>
									<p>Wooden roller (155mm high). </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
